segments.text: Stangle, would you tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, and if you know them, the dates of their birth and death and the places of that, the date and place of your birth, and whatever schools you attended before you went to A&M and any other childhood recollections that you may have.
Well, Mr. Schultz, I was born
in Stangleville, Wisconsin in 1889 and came to Texas in 1897.
I forget just exactly what.
And the reason for coming to Texas and leaving Wisconsin where I was born
was a terrible loss that my father entailed while I was just a youngster.
This was a financial loss?
Financial loss, yes.
In other words, he was in the lumber and flour mill business, and they had a flood.
And he lost all the lumber because it was stacked on the banks.
The banks caved in, and it went down Lake Michigan.
And his flour was in sacks, stored, and became paste, you see.
So all of his income was lost.
And of course, it just discouraged him, and he decided he'd get away from it just as far as he could.
Although we did have a farm, and we lived on that farm for a couple of years before we came.
In Texas, we came to Bryan, Texas.
Our father's cousin was a Catholic priest, and he was the one who was responsible for getting us to Texas.
As you know, the Swift and Armour built their plants in Fort Worth, and he figured that would be a good place to take a large family, and that's where we moved to, to Fort Worth.
What was your father's name?
My father's name was John, John J. Stangle.
And your mother's name was what?
My mother.
mother's name is Anne, and you want her maiden name is Seidenglanz, S-E-I-D-E-N-G-L-A-N-Z, Seidenglanz.
You'll find a lot of this material in Who's Who in America.
You say you were a large family.
How many brothers and sisters did you have?
Well, of course, the original family, I had two sisters and two brothers.
Now, that is the original family.
And my father married me.
And there's five children in that family.
And then he separated from his second wife.
My mother died before I had a chance to know her.
I never did know my mother.
And there's five children in that family.
So they're scattered all over the United States, you might say.
Well, I suppose maybe that's about all the background you need on.
Do you remember anything about the trip from Wisconsin to Texas?
Yeah, I do.
Of course, we were moved, with the help of my uncles, to a loading dock, we'll say, on Lake Michigan.
And we went in a ship on Lake Michigan to Chicago.
And in Chicago, we caught a train and came by rail to Bryan, Texas.
And that was in the mid-'90s?
That is in the mid-'90s, yes.
I don't know.
I think it was 97, to be honest.
I think so.
Did you then attend school sometime in Bryan?
Did I?
Yes.
In other words, I think it was third grade when I attended Catholic school, and then of course later a public school, and I went to school there until my seventh grade, I think.
Then your family moved to Fort Worth.
Family moved to Fort Worth, yes.
When they moved to Fort Worth, of course I moved with them and enrolled in Texas A&M from Fort Worth.
So you completed your high school, your schooling in Fort Worth then.
Right.
How did you happen to choose Texas A&M?
There was just, in my class, graduating class, there were 10 students, eight girls and two boys, and I was one of the boys.
And there was only one, two institutions that we knew, that is Texas A&M and University of Texas.
And since we were in Fort Worth, neither one of us had the desire to go to University of Texas.
So we graduated in 1910.
And this other graduate, a boy,
decided that he was going to college, and he selected Texas A&M.
I didn't select Texas A&M.
In fact, I didn't intend going to college because my parents weren't able to send me.
But when September came, practically every member of that class went off to college somewhere.
For instance, Mrs. Dupree, who lives here in Lubbock, went to Oberlin.
And, of course, John Condon was the boy, and he went to Texas A&M.
And a lot of these others went.
For instance, one girl, of course most of them are dead now, went to West Texas State at Canyon.
Another one there, Monty Brown, I forget just what school she went to school.
So they all went somewhere, and I was left in Fort Worth holding a bag.
And so I got to thinking.
I was working for Arm and Company, getting the seventeen and a half cents an hour.
And I went to my father, and I says, if I work and save my money, can I go to college?
He said, yes, and I'll help you all I can.
So I enrolled in Texas A&M.
I did a little bit of checking in your senior yearbook, and I believe there it said you
somewhere there indicated you had worked for Swift for a couple years and for the Dunham's Percheron Farm.
Yeah.
Where was that?
Now this Dunham's Percheron Farm was in Wayne, Illinois, and I worked there during the summer, not during the regular session.
That was during the summer while you were at A&M.
Well, I was at A&M, yes.
My first summer on that farm was in 19...
I guess 1912, because I enrolled in 1910, 1911.
I enrolled at A&M in 1911.
So you did stay out one year between high school and...
Yeah, I did stay out one year working to earn enough money to go to college, and I saved over $700.
Was that working at 17 cents an hour?
Well, no, I did better than that.
I got increases, gradual increases in salary, and when I left to go to A&M, I was getting 25 cents an hour.
which was a white-collar job.
And, of course, they told me, we wouldn't go to A&M.
We'd go stay here and work for SWIFT.
SWIFT will take care of you.
And I said, no, I'm going to college.
This was the people at SWIFT that told you that?
Yeah.
Did you go through any particular special procedures to go to Texas A&M?
Did you have to apply for admission or something like that?
No, I was a graduate.
I was of Northside High School.
It was North Fort Worth when I enrolled there.
But during the time, during my last two years, it became Northside High School.
And that's when I graduated in 1910 from Northside High School.
So then all you had to do was get on the train and go down to College Station and register.
Yeah, but I didn't go with this fellow with whom I graduated the same time I did.
I went with another boy from Fort Worth, and his name was Fisher.
John Curran Godfrey Fisher, we called him J.K. Fisher, we called him Blondie.
And he had been there the previous year, so he knew the ropes, you see.
And I became his roommate at A&M in Miller Hall.
So he was a sophomore and you were a fish.
I was a fish, right.
And...
Were you his man, so to speak, then?
Did you have to do a few jobs for him?
Well, of course, I didn't do all of them for him, but I did a lot of jobs.
When you arrived there on campus and registered, and you were a fish in K Company, I believe.
the same company Fisher was in?
No, he was in I Company.
He was in I Company.
But I and K lived, were in the same dorm?
Right, in the same dorm.
And you see there's four companies to a battalion.
And there's two, the outside companies were the tall fellas, and the inside companies were the short fellas.
So I got in
the company that had the short fellas, and there was a little maneuvering there.
But I got in I Company, that is the second year, not the first year.
The first year I was definitely in K Company.
You didn't have any choice in that then?
No, not the first year.
The second year, I did.
When they asked me, what company do you want to get in?
I said, I want an eye company.
He said, stand under that marker.
And he looked at me and said, you're too short.
You can't get an eye company.
And so he says, see Sargent Zone.
talk to him.
So I went over to see Sargent and so on and so on.
And I said, I want to get an eye company.
He says, why do you want to get an eye company?
I said, I'm rooming with a boy from Fort Worth.
Both of us are poor boys.
And we're going to buy our books together and share a lot of our expenses.
And that's really
So he wrote on this instance card, let's see, how did he put that?
K Company, I Company of Room.
So the next sergeant says, well, which company do you want in?
I said, I Company.
K Company, I Company, I mean K Company, I Company room, so they had room in I Company.
So I got in I Company.
And so you know from your experience, the first week at A&M, they landed
line up these students, and of course you'd line them up in the company by size.
And in my company, they started with these tall boys over here, and they came down, down, down, down.
Here I was the last one.
And this captain, Wade Burleson,
He looked at me a while and says, he says, Ron, what the hell do you want in this company?
I says, I want a room with J.K. Fisher.
And he says, well, I'll let you stay in the eye company.
He says, you're too short.
I'll let you stay in the eye company.
And I'll try to cover you up, hide you.
And so he did.
That first week put me in the rear rank, the smallest group of eight, and I stayed in I Company until I returned to A&M after I left A&M in between enrolling and graduating.
What were your first reactions to the school when you arrived?
Well, I was very favorably impressed.
And I took the mucks with me.
What I'll say, I took the bricks and the bats both, you know.
And I spent my first night in a tent.
We had tents in those days.
And then, of course, I got with this room with Fisher.
Fisher and I had a room on a third, what we called stoop, third stoop, in Milner Hall.
And Milner Hall was right next to where Subiza Hall is now, but Subiza Hall wasn't there then.
You had the Ole Miss Hall there.
Yeah.
You were there during the fire of the old mess hall.
Right.
I imagine that was some exciting times.
Oh, well, it was.
When the mess hall burned.
The old main burned.
The old main building burned.
Then we had, of course, well, I can tell you a lot of things that happened about that time.
What sort of things?
Well, for instance, whenever...
When the mess hall burned, they built a temporary mess hall out of tin, you know.
And they got it built during the Christmas holidays.
And by marching us to meals, by the time they said, take seats, everything on the table was cold.
And if so, we didn't enjoy our meals at all.
This was in the temporary mess hall.
Temporary mess hall.
And we were all dissatisfied because we'd all come home after having had good meals and being taken care of and so on and so forth.
So things were just not right with us.
And I don't know that anybody has talked to you about the strike.
We didn't have a strike, but we did say we'd do certain things if you'll do certain things.
In other words, we're not going to classes under these conditions.
But we will attend our military obligations.
We'll march according to schedule, and we'll line up for our march to meals and so on.
Do everything that we have to do that pertains to military.
But as far as pertaining to academics, we quit.
I took, I think, possibly three exams.
before the president warned us, says, now you have one of two choices.
You can either stay, carry on as you carried on before this thing happened, or you can just pack your bags and trunks and take it out for home.
Well, that's what we did.
466 of us signed a petition not to go to class.
And so we did go to class, and I was one of those that packed up and went home.
This was in what, 1913?
This was 1913.
And of course, not all of them left because they figured it was pretty dirty to take out on those 1913 boys.
not have a final parade, but we did have a final parade for the 1913 class.
When the parade was over, things broke up.
We scattered everywhere and of course went home.
When I arrived home,
My father met me, mouth wide open, and asked to say, What are you doing here? I said, Wait a minute.
Let me talk. So I told him what had gone on and what had happened and so on, and I couldnt say.
Thats when I left and went to Dunhams Perchard Farm in Wayne, Illinois.
This was in the latter part of January.
I stayed there and worked until September of 1913.
This fellow, Fisher, came up there and worked with me that summer.
And so I became kind of a horseman, and of course they wanted me to stay there and work with horses, but I said, no, I'm going to college.
So then the uproar about in 13 was sparked by the unsatisfactory food after the fire in the mess hall?
Right.
Uh-huh.
That plus some other things.
We had some illness that was serious.
We had a very popular student who died from a cut vein.
He was hanging a picture and ended up up on a chair and jumped off this chair and the glass broke and he cut a
He died in that room, just bled to death right there.
He was a very popular fellow named Leonard, August Leonard.
Then we had some undue hazing and we didn't take this.
take this hazing, and so those that were most serious in this hazing were expelled, about 21 of them.
And that upset us, you see.
This was when Milner was president, right?
Yeah, Milner was president.
Was there anything comparable to that developed after the Old Main fire?
I believe that was before the mess hall, wasn't it?
Yeah.
You mean this fire?
No.
The mess hall had already burned up.
The mess hall burned first and then Old Main?
First, yeah.
After the Old Main burned, what did you do for classrooms?
A lot of classes had been held in Old Main, had there not?
Yes.
Now, that's lost me.
I don't recall just exactly where we, just where we held classes.
And, of course, the library was lost at that point, what there was of it.
Yeah.
Because I know I helped carry books.
Well, I think possibly...
Maybe part of the Old Main building was saved, and we used the rooms that were saved there for classrooms, because I recall carrying books up there and getting paid 15 cents an hour for doing it.
Well, from what pictures I've seen, it was nothing but a few brick, some of the outside brick walls left after the fire.
You mean the Old Main?
Old Main building, yeah.
Maybe that's it.
But then, of course, they started the new building pretty soon after that.
Right away.
Yeah, and it was completed in 14, I believe.
Except for the food that wasn't so good after the mess hall burned, what would you say about the food in the mess hall before the fire?
Was it pretty good?
Yeah, it was all right.
In other words, we complained about the food, all of us,
gained weight, so I didn't particularly kick on the food.
Of course, I had a job, and I wasn't eating with the Corps as a sophomore, junior, and senior.
I was working with the Horse Guard.
And you ate?
what we call work table.
Uh-huh.
Was this all the boys who had jobs?
Who had jobs, involved work in the morning, ate at the same place, work table, you see.
Uh-huh.
This would include, did you have students who worked, waited tables in the mess hall?
Did we?
Yes.
Yes.
Uh-huh.
And they ate at the work table.
Work table.
Either that or they just grabbed something before they went to class and so on.
What about you were still in school when Sbisa Hall was open, were you not?
When Sbisa Hall, the new mess hall was completed?
Yes, I was.
I guess it was completed during Dr. Mazzello's time.
Oh, I'm sure it was because, well, I don't know.
How long were you fed in the temporary mess hall?
I think the rest of that year.
But of course, I wasn't there.
I was one of those that took out.
So I think the new mess hall had been built while I was gone.
I see.
And so how was the food there?
Pretty good?
Very good, yeah.
What privileges did the upperclassmen have that the freshmen didn't have?
Could the upperclassmen do things like leave campus and things of that nature that the freshmen couldn't?
Yeah, they could get a permit.
They'd have to get a permit from the commandant, and they could have a date once a month.
They could have a dance once a month.
Freshmen didn't have any privileges at all, except for going to class and getting their tail licked.
It didn't bother me.
On that third stoop, I ran around it many a time.
You know, upperclassmen were up there with their belts, giving us crack on the butt.
What kinds of things did you do for entertainment or recreation during the years you were there?
Well, I did not have a date until my junior year.
Was that for one of the big dances?
One of the big, yes.
That was my first date.
Then I think I had two more after that as a senior.
So I didn't date in the first place.
I didn't have money.
to bring a girl down there and keep a girl until I didn't have many dates.
I remember the girls very well.
One of them was from Fort Worth and the other one was from Houston.
Did you have a place where you could play dominoes or anything like that?
No.
What about, could you play cards?
No.
Was that against the rules?
That was against the rules.
Could you smoke?
Yeah.
Cigarettes or cigars or both?
Both.
Cigars cost a nickel.
And that's when I started smoking cigars.
I still smoke cigars now.
And I bought one of these aluminum holders, you know.
I like that.
